public class SingletonDoubleCheck {
private SingletonDoubleCheck instance = null;

public SingletonDoubleCheck getInstance() {
if (instance == null) {
synchronized (SingletonDoubleCheck.class) {
if (instance == null) {
instance = new SingletonDoubleCheck();
}
}
}
return instance;
}
}

The above-mentioned code is for creating a Singleton class. But this
code is not thread-safe.

In this we check the value of instance second time in the
synchronized block. But the JIT compiler can rearrange the
Bytecode in such a way that the reference to SingletonDoubleCheck 
instance will be set before the execution of constructor.

Due to this the method getInstance() will return an object that may
not have been initialized properly.

We can use the keyword volatile for instance to make this thread-
safe code.

Any variables that is marked as volatile will be visible to other
threads only after the completion of the constructor of the object.

